{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=CrocefissioneRaffaello.jpg | title=Crucifixion with the Virgin, Saints and Angels | artist=[[Raphael]] | year=1502–3 | type=[[Oil painting|Oil on poplar]] | height_metric=283.3 | width_metric=167.3 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[London]] | museum=[[National Gallery (London)|National Gallery]] }} The '''''Mond Crucifixion''''' (or '''''Crocifissione Gavari'''''; both names are after former owners) is a [[painting]] by the [[Italy|Italian]] [[renaissance]] artist [[Raphael]].
An early work influenced by [[Perugino]], it was originally an [[altarpiece]] in the church of [[San Domenico, Città di Castello]], near Raphael's hometown of [[Urbino]]. The painting shows [[Jesus]] on the cross, who is looking peaceful even though he is dying. There are two angels catching his blood in chalices. On Jesus' left kneels [[Mary Magdalene]], with [[John the Evangelist]] standing behind her. On his right [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Mary]] stands, and [[Jerome|St. Jerome]], to whom the altar was dedicated, is kneeling. At the foot of the cross is the inscription <small>RAPHAEL/ VRBIN / AS /.P.[INXIT]</small> ("Raphael of Urbino painted this") in silver letters.
The painting was bequeathed to the [[National Gallery, London|National Gallery]] by [[Ludwig Mond]].
The sun and moon at the top are present despite the [[First Council of Constantinople|Council of Constantinople]] prohibition of such symbology for its reference to other religions.{{dubious|date=July 2017}}
==Painting materials== The painting was analyzed in the National Gallery London<ref>Roy, A., Spring, M., Plazzotta, C. ‘Raphael’s Early Work in the National Gallery: Paintings before Rome‘. National Gallery Technical Bulletin Vol 25, pp 4–35.</ref> and the typical [[pigments]] of the [[Renaissance]] period were identified. He painted the Crucifixion among other pigments with natural [[ultramarine]], [[lead-tin-yellow]], [[verdigris]], [[vermilion]] and [[ochres]]<ref>[http://colourlex.com/project/raphael-moon-crucifixion/ Raphael, The Mond Crucifixion], ColourLex</ref>
